Again, I should stress all three of us are fine if tired.

There must be lots of birth partners out there who have witnessed similar or even worse. So I wonder about the mental health toll and support for partners too. Again, I think longer paternity leave is needed because of the physical and mental health impact on both partners.
I was on gas and air at the time for pain relief, so not very with it. However, afterwards he told me there had been a lot of blood.
I sustained third degree tears after giving birth and was rushed into emergency surgery due to blood loss. My husband left holding our baby.

It can obviously be traumatic process for the mother (not always as some people have really positive births and birth experiences). But it can be equally hard for the birth partner who has to watch the other person go through childbirth.

Before I start this next thread, I should say I'm fine as is my husband and our baby. I currently have a sleeping infant in my lap as I tweet this.

I recently started thinking about the potential trauma of childbirth on a partner.

I should add: I'm fine and my little one has made it through the tough fourth trimester. However, I really feel we need changes in terms of paternity leave, support, childbirth and women's health.

*That should read:

You might also have other things like tears, infections or other complications. So while you're recovering, you need support.
There's the mental health aspect as  well. It can be quite isolating caring for a baby yourself and again struggling without much sleep.
You might also have other things. I ended up with tears, infections or other complications. So while you're recovering, you need support.
Then you've got c-sections which have a minimum six-week recovery period. Again, during this time, you need support looking after your child.

Childbirth is a huge thing too - something I would compare to major surgery. But unlike an operation where you have time to recover, you don't with becoming a parent. Instead you now have a tiny human to keep alive while your body   begins to recuperate.
The mother or primary caregiver needs help, particularly with sleep deprivation meaning it's exhausting trying to cope day and night singlehandedly.
Paternity leave needs to be longer than just two weeks. It's simply not enough time for so many reasons. Having a newborn is a life changing experience and it's gruelling.

Should add, induction is of course necessary but are there new methods out there which can use the trauma? Giving birth can be traumatic enough as it is without induction.

I also feel women need more information and advice before giving birth such as lots of advice and information on the importance of perineal massage and pelvic floor exercises. Again, more information is a positive. Pregnancy and childbirth and parenthood needs to be demystified.
I'm simply posing the question as I feel in my bones there needs to be change to make childbirth and induction less traumatic.

Perhaps it's time to come up with new methods of induction which perhaps focus on the more psychological and mental aspects of preparing to give birth?
Some of the mothers I spoke to felt disempowered after ending up on the induction pathway with induction method after induction method tried.

When it comes to women's sexual health give us information and options so we can make informed decisions which suit us.

I've also been thinking a lot about labour and childbirth. Surely, there should be some kind of postnatal mental health check. Going through something like that is huge and life altering.
